         <abstract>
            <p>Towards the end of 1966 inventories began piling sky high; the rate of their accumulation reached a record for the postwar period. Since sales rates were sagging, the inventory-sales ratio moved up sharply. The concern over rising inventories caused a reaction on the part of businessmen to reduce their stockpiles. The author examines the impact of the ensuing slowdown of inventory accumulation on business and submits a theory of the underlying relationship between inventories and the economy.</p>
          </abstract>
